merge_data<- merge(rating_data,basics_data,by="tconst", all= TRUE)
merge_data<-data.frame(merge_data$tconst,merge_data$averageRating,merge_data$startYear,merge_data$runtimeMinutes, merge_data$numVotes)

merge_data = merge_data %>% drop_na()

merge_data <- merge_data %>% 
  rename(
    tconst = merge_data.tconst,
    averageRating = merge_data.averageRating,
    startYear = merge_data.startYear,
    runtimeMinutes = merge_data.runtimeMinutes,
    numVotes = merge_data.numVotes
    )
q1 = quantile(merge_data$runtimeMinutes,0.25)
q3 = quantile(merge_data$runtimeMinutes,0.75)
iqr = IQR(merge_data$runtimeMinutes)
upper = q1 + 1.5*iqr
lower = q3- 1.5*iqr
merge_data = subset(merge_data, runtimeMinutes > lower & runtimeMinutes < upper)
library(mgcv)

model = gam(averageRating ~ s(startYear, k = 12)+s(runtimeMinutes, k=12), weights = numVotes, data = merge_data)
summary(model)

model.fit = predict(model,merge_data[,c("startYear","runtimeMinutes")])
merge_data = data.frame(merge_data, pred_rating = as.vector(model.fit))

Initially, we tried fitting linear models, but as there is no linearity between average movie ratings and length of the movie, We decided to use GAM(general additive model) to fit this non-linear relationship between the variables. Also, we used the degree as 2 while displaying the model using method.args in the ggplot.

a)There is no transformation required for any of the variables as the plots looked identical with or without the transformations

(b)There is no strong linear relationship between the average rating and the running time. Hence fitting a curved model helped determine the actual relationship

c)An addtive model is adequate for this problem because ther are non linearities in the data and GAMS can be used to further smooth the non linear curves like splines, polynomials,etc.

d)Yes, it is required to filter/downweight the tail values as these outliers tends to dominate the plot. The running time outliers were removed by using interquartile range.

e)Yes, it is necessary to give weights by number of votes as if only 1 person voted for a given movie, it doesn’t tell the accurate rating of the movie.

  1. Facet plot displaying the model that predicts the IMDB ratings on the basis of the running time of the movie. The facet plot is split with a span of 6 years from the startYear:
ggplot(merge_data,aes(x=runtimeMinutes,y=averageRating))+
geom_point(aes(size = numVotes),alpha=0.1) +
facet_wrap(~cut_number(startYear, n = 6, ncol=2))+
geom_smooth(aes(weight = numVotes),method.args = list(degree = 2), se = F)+
ggtitle("Relationship between average movie ratings and length of movie by year")+
xlab("Length of movie")+ylab("Average IMDB Movie Rating")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

From the facet plot it can be observe that:

  1. In the years 1874-1976, the average rating of the movies with close to 0 minutes of running time is the lowest among all the year brackets.

  2. In all the years, the movies with a running time of around 45-60 minutes have the highest average rating. Whereas, the movies with the running time of around 120 minutes have the lowest average IMDB ratings.

  3. Also, the average IMDB rating starts increasing after gradually increasing the running time of the movies from 90 minutes.

3.Plotting the above model using raster-and-contour plots, in order to visualize the relationship in 3D:

ggplot(merge_data, aes(x = startYear, y = runtimeMinutes, fill = pred_rating)) + geom_raster(aes(fill = pred_rating)) +coord_fixed() + 
scale_fill_distiller(palette = 'RdYlBu') + 
geom_tile()+
xlab("Start year of the movie") +
ylab("Length of the movie (in min)") + 
ggtitle("Contour plot of length of movie with start year") + 
labs(fill="Predicted Movie Rating") 
## Warning in f(...): Raster pixels are placed at uneven horizontal intervals
## and will be shifted. Consider using geom_tile() instead.

The given contour plot shows that:

  1. The predicted movie rating for the earlier years is relatively low as compared to recent years(as we can see many blue dots representing those years)

  2. There’s a light colored patch for movies of length 90 minutes from the years 1960-2020. This patch denotes the movie rating between 6 and 7.

  3. Over the years, the movies with the length of 60 minutes have the highest average IMDB movie ratings

  1. It can be seen that the average IMDB ratings of the movie is dependent on the release year of a particular movie. This can be seen from the two plots as the movies with a length of approximately 60 minutes had an average rating of 9, which decreased gradually after the year 2020.
